pr_review_comments:
[{'comment_id': 938728715, 'comment_body': 'Add a CPython test too:
```suggestion
RUN(NAME generics_array_01   LABELS cpython llvm)
```', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2022, 8, 5, 11, 39, 48, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'certik', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 939087437, 'comment_body': 'The problem is that a TypeVar object, in this case T, is not subscriptable in CPython.', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2022, 8, 5, 18, 28, 53, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'ansharlubis', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 939105185, 'comment_body': 'I see, that is indeed a problem.

I think we should probably design our own "TypeVar" that can handle subscripting, we'll add it to `ltypes` and we have to make sure exactly the same syntax works both in LPython and CPython.', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2022, 8, 5, 18, 41, 10, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'certik', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 939678626, 'comment_body': 'A more interesting case would be to support `def f(lst: T[...], i: T) -> T`.
